Overall conclusion

The clearest treatment-biomarker pattern was KRAS G12C-specific sotorasib benefit: the adjusted interaction and the KRAS G12C subgroup comparison were both large, positive, and highly significant. The broader matched targeted-therapy indicator was also strongly positive, but the individual EGFR/osimertinib and BRCA2/olaparib analyses were not supported, so the pooled targeted-therapy result should be interpreted as mainly reflecting the KRAS G12C/sotorasib signal in this cohort. Pembrolizumab did not show significant unselected benefit or significant positive modification by PD-L1 TPS, TMB-high status, STK11 mutation, autoimmune disease, or above-median PD-L1.

The strongest prognostic patterns were clinical rather than broad targeted-therapy effects: older age was associated with longer PFS, female sex with shorter PFS, and higher ECOG performance status, stage IV disease, brain metastases, weight loss, squamous histology, current smoking, low albumin, high LDH, and heart failure were adverse. Several plausible markers were refuted or weak in adjusted models, including liver metastases, bone metastases, CRP, NLR, hemoglobin, alkaline phosphatase, sodium, calcium, COPD, chronic kidney disease, interstitial lung disease history, most rare driver alterations, and the osimertinib and olaparib biomarker interactions.

 succeeded in 1390ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc: 50000 NSCLC records; mean pfs_months 3.43 (SD 2.23).

I ran 25 propose-test-refine iterations using linear models for pfs_months. Baseline-adjusted models controlled for age_years, sex_female, stage_iv, ecog_ps, has_brain_mets, albumin_g_dl, ldh_u_l, weight_loss_pct_6mo, crp_mg_l, nlr, smoking_status, and histology unless otherwise noted. P-values use large-sample normal approximations to the OLS coefficient tests.

General disease-status effects were partly concentrated in a few variables. Higher albumin_g_dl was strongly favorable, while higher weight_loss_pct_6mo and ldh_u_l were adverse. Stage IV disease and brain metastases had large negative adjusted associations. In contrast, crp_mg_l, nlr, liver_mets, bone_mets, pleural_effusion, adrenal_mets, and most other metastatic-site flags were weak or not significant after adjustment.

The clearest treatment-biomarker pattern was treatment_sotorasib by kras_g12c. The interaction was large and strongly positive in both focused and joint models. The other matched-treatment hypotheses were refuted: treatment_osimertinib by egfr_mutation, treatment_olaparib by brca2_mutation, and treatment_pembrolizumab by tmb_high were near zero and not significant.

Immunotherapy-specific hypotheses were mostly unsupported. Pembrolizumab interactions with tmb_high, pdl1_tps, stk11_mutation, egfr_mutation, liver_mets, histology_squamous, and current smoking were all small and not significant. The main exception was a small negative treatment_pembrolizumab by kras_g12c interaction, about -0.053 months, which was statistically significant but much smaller than the sotorasib by KRAS G12C effect.

Exploratory scans reinforced that most interaction signals were small. The top pembrolizumab scan terms were under 0.10 months in absolute value. The osimertinib scan did not identify egfr_mutation as a dominant interaction; the largest scanned osimertinib interactions were also small, with only pleural_effusion reaching nominal significance.

Overall conclusion: the dominant supported signals are a large positive sotorasib benefit in kras_g12c patients and strong baseline prognostic effects from albumin, weight loss, LDH, stage IV disease, and brain metastases. Many plausible NSCLC treatment-biomarker hypotheses were directly tested and refuted in this dataset.

Selected effect estimates:
- sotorasib x kras_g12c: 2.535 months, p=<1e-300
- osimertinib x egfr_mutation: -0.022 months, p=0.2120
- olaparib x brca2_mutation: -0.035 months, p=0.3280
- pembrolizumab x tmb_high: -0.001 months, p=0.9581
- pembrolizumab x stk11_mutation: -0.003 months, p=0.8644
- albumin_g_dl per 1 g/dL: 0.454 months, p=<1e-300
- weight_loss_pct_6mo per 5 points: -0.365 months, p=<1e-300
- stage_iv: -1.418 months, p=<1e-300
- has_brain_mets: -0.917 months, p=<1e-300

 succeeded in 1558ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc: 50000 NSCLC patient records with pfs_months as the continuous outcome. I ran 25 propose-test-refine iterations using adjusted ordinary least-squares models and targeted subgroup mean comparisons. Adjusted models included demographics, stage, brain metastases, albumin, LDH, weight loss, CRP, NLR, ECOG performance status, histology, smoking, treatments, and key biomarkers unless otherwise noted.

The strongest general prognostic signals were clinical status and disease burden. Older age was unexpectedly associated with longer PFS: 1.684 months per 10-year higher age_years (p=0.000). In contrast, stage IV disease (-1.417 months, p=0.000), ECOG 2 versus 0 (-2.177 months, p=0.000), brain metastases (-0.912 months, p=0.000), squamous histology (-0.723 months, p=0.000), current versus never smoking (-0.545 months, p=0.000), and sex_female (-0.203 months, p=0.000) were all independently associated with shorter PFS.

Nutritional and tumor-burden laboratory features also tracked PFS. Each 1 percentage-point higher weight_loss_pct_6mo had a -0.073 month coefficient for PFS (p=0.000), each 1 g/dL higher albumin_g_dl had a 0.463 month coefficient (p=0.000), and each 100 U/L higher ldh_u_l had a -0.045 month coefficient (p=0.000).

The clearest treatment signal was biomarker-specific sotorasib benefit. The adjusted sotorasib main effect was 0.323 months (p=0.000), and the treatment_sotorasib by kras_g12c interaction was large and positive: 2.533 months (p=0.000). In the KRAS G12C subgroup, mean PFS was 2.552 months higher with sotorasib (p=0.000), while the KRAS G12C-negative subgroup showed no benefit (-0.005 months, p=0.799). Additional sotorasib interactions were negative for egfr_mutation (-0.208 months, p=0.000), alk_fusion (-0.343 months, p=0.000), and brca2_mutation (-0.328 months, p=0.000), with a smaller positive interaction for tmb_high (0.076 months, p=5.40e-7).

Several plausible biomarker and treatment hypotheses were not supported. stk11_mutation was only weakly adverse (-0.019 months, p=0.037), and brca2_mutation was independently adverse (-0.109 months, p=8.16e-9). However, pembrolizumab had no positive adjusted association (-0.006 months, p=0.383), pdl1_tps had no meaningful main effect (0.003 months per 0.50 higher value, p=0.668), and the pembrolizumab by pdl1_tps interaction was null (0.004 months, p=0.781). Similarly, there was no evidence of biomarker-concordant benefit for osimertinib in egfr_mutation (-0.020 interaction months, p=0.335) or olaparib in brca2_mutation (-0.004 interaction months, p=0.930).

Overall, this cohort showed strong prognostic structure and one dominant predictive treatment interaction: sotorasib benefit was concentrated in KRAS G12C-positive disease. The evidence did not support the expected pembrolizumab-PD-L1, osimertinib-EGFR, or olaparib-BRCA2 benefit patterns in this dataset. The age and sex findings are notable because their directions are not the usual clinical expectation, so they should be treated as dataset-specific associations rather than causal conclusions.

